T1  - LABOR MARKET SEARCH, INFORMALITY, AND SCHOOLING INVESTMENTS
AU  - Bobba, Matteo
AU  - Flabbi, Luca
AU  - Levy, Santiago
Y1  - 2022/02/01
PY  - 2022
DA  - 2022/02/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12536
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 211
EP  - 259
VL  - 63
IS  - 1
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12536
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Abstract We develop a search and matching model where jobs can be formal or informal. Workers choose schooling and search for jobs. Firms post vacancies in each schooling market and decide the job's formality status. Upon meeting, workers and firms bargain over wages. The equilibrium size of the informal sector is an endogenous function of labor market fundamentals and institutions. We estimate the model using labor force survey data from Mexico and exploiting the exogenous variation induced by a noncontributory social program. Counterfactual experiments show that eliminating informal jobs increases schooling investments but decreases welfare for both workers and firms.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - OBVIOUSLY STRATEGY-PROOF IMPLEMENTATION OF ASSIGNMENT RULES: A NEW CHARACTERIZATION
AU  - Mandal, Pinaki
AU  - Roy, Souvik
Y1  - 2022/02/01
PY  - 2022
DA  - 2022/02/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12538
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 261
EP  - 290
VL  - 63
IS  - 1
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12538
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Abstract We consider assignment problems where individuals are to be assigned at most one indivisible object and monetary transfers are not allowed. We provide a characterization of assignment rules that are Pareto efficient, nonbossy, and implementable in obviously strategy-proof (OSP) mechanisms. As corollaries of our result, we obtain a characterization of OSP-implementable fixed priority top trading cycles (FPTTC) rules, hierarchical exchange rules, and trading cycles rules. Troyan (International Economic Review 60 (2019), 1249?61) provides a characterization of OSP-implementable FPTTC rules when there are equal number of individuals and objects. Our result generalizes this for arbitrary values of those.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - GLOBAL INFLUENCES ON GENDER INEQUALITY: EVIDENCE FROM FEMALE EMPLOYMENT IN KOREA
AU  - Choi, Jaerim
AU  - Greaney, Theresa M.
Y1  - 2022/02/01
PY  - 2022
DA  - 2022/02/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12539
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 291
EP  - 328
VL  - 63
IS  - 1
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12539
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Abstract Do multinational enterprises (MNEs) transfer gender-equal employment practices across borders? Using firm-level data for Korea, a country with low gender equality, we find evidence that MNEs bring their home countries' gender norms in employment with them. Foreign-acquired firms report 2?12 percentage-points higher female shares of permanent main-task workers at firm headquarters compared with nonacquired firms and the differential increases with the level of gender equality in the MNEs? home countries. We estimate that 1 to 7 percent of the productivity increase caused by foreign acquisition can be attributed to workforce reorganization that may reduce gender-based misallocations of talent.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - A SEARCH MODEL OF EARLY EMPLOYMENT CAREERS AND YOUTH CRIME
AU  - Mancino, M. Antonella
Y1  - 2022/02/01
PY  - 2022
DA  - 2022/02/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12540
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 329
EP  - 390
VL  - 63
IS  - 1
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12540
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Abstract A large fraction of disadvantaged young individuals makes money from crime, and yet their labor market is usually studied ignoring the presence of the criminal sector. Consistent with the empirical evidence, I build a two-sector model of frictional labor search to study crime and employment outcomes jointly, and estimate it using a panel data set of young offenders. I use the model to illustrate sizable interactions between sectors, and show that, aiming at the same reduction in crime, policies targeting the legal labor sector generate larger welfare gains, and at a comparable cost, than traditional policies focusing on the criminal sector.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - PARAMETRIC CONDITIONAL MEAN INFERENCE WITH FUNCTIONAL DATA APPLIED TO LIFETIME INCOME CURVES
AU  - Cho, Jin Seo
AU  - Phillips, Peter C. B.
AU  - Seo, Juwon
