T1  - SPECIALIZED LEARNING AND POLITICAL POLARIZATION
AU  - Yuksel, Sevgi
Y1  - 2022/02/01
PY  - 2022
DA  - 2022/02/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12555
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 457
EP  - 474
VL  - 63
IS  - 1
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12555
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Abstract When citizens are differentiated by how much they care about different issues informing policy, specialization allows them to concentrate their learning on the issues that are most important to them. However, as different citizens focus on different issues, the electorate becomes less responsive to party platforms. In particular, equilibrium policies polarize more in fractionalized societies in which there is greater disagreement about which issues matter the most. When the learning technology allows for more specialization, it effectively transforms the society into a more fractionalized one without changing the underlying preferences of the electorate, thereby increasing polarization.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - DISTRIBUTIONAL AND HOUSING PRICE EFFECTS FROM PUBLIC TRANSIT INVESTMENT: EVIDENCE FROM VANCOUVER
AU  - Chernoff, Alex
AU  - Craig, Andrea N.
Y1  - 2022/02/01
PY  - 2022
DA  - 2022/02/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12556
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 475
EP  - 509
VL  - 63
IS  - 1
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12556
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Abstract We estimate a residential sorting model using microdata to study an expansion of the Vancouver rapid transit network. Our results indicate that many aspects of household preferences were stable over time; however, preferences for transit access became more homogeneous with respect to income. Simulations show that these preference changes, along with endogenous housing appreciation and rising income levels in connected neighborhoods, result in larger benefits for higher-income households. This distributional pattern is driven by the gains of households working in pre-connected neighborhoods. In contrast, the benefits to those working in newly connected neighborhoods disproportionately favor lower-income households.
ER  - 

